  <exercisegroup>
    <title>Pour se pratiquer</title>

    <exercise>
          <statement><p>
          Est-ce que <m>\vnabla\times \vF</m> doit être perpendiculaire à <m>\vF</m>?
          </p></statement>

          <hint><p>
          Calculer <m>\vnabla\times \vF</m> pour quelques champs de vecteurs simples.
          </p></hint>

          <answer><p>
          Non.
          </p></answer>

          <solution><p>
          No.  The vector field <m>\vF(x,y,z) = \vi +y\,\vk</m> has
          <md>
          <mrow>
          \vnabla\times \vF
          &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix} \vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk
          </mrow><mrow>
                                     \pdiff{}{x} &amp; \pdiff{}{y} &amp; \pdiff{}{z}
          </mrow><mrow>
                                     1 &amp; 0 &amp; y
                      \end{matrix}\right]
          </mrow><mrow>
          &amp;=\vi
          </mrow>
          </md>
          has dot product <m>1</m> with <m>\vF(x,y,z)</m> (for all <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, <m>z</m>) and
          so is not perpendicular to it.
          </p></solution>
        </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Évaluer <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF</m> et <m>\vnabla\times\vF</m> pour chacun des champs de vecteurs suivants.
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li> <m>\vF=x\,\vi+y\,\vj+z\,\vk</m>
      </li>
      <li> <m>\vF=xy^2\vi-yz^2\vj+zx^2\vk</m>
      </li>
      <li> <m>\vF=\frac{x\vi+y\vj}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}</m>
                     (le vecteur polaire de base <m>\hat{\bf r}</m> en 2D)
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>\vF=\frac{-y\vi+x\vj}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}</m>
            (le vecteur polaire de base <m>\hat{\pmb{\theta}}</m> en 2D)
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p>

      </statement>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF=3</m>, <m>\vnabla\times\vF=\vZero</m>
      </p>

      <p>(b) <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF=y^2-z^2+x^2</m>,
          <m>\vnabla\times\vF=2yz\,\vi-2xz\,\vj-2xy\,\vk</m>
      </p>

      <p>(c) <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF=\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}</m>,
          <m>\vnabla\times\vF=\vZero</m>
      </p>

      <p>(d) <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF=0</m>, <m>\vnabla\times\vF=\frac{\vk}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}</m>
      </p>

      </answer>

      <solution><p>
      (a)
      By definition
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla\cdot(x\,\vi+y\,\vj+z\,\vk)
      &amp;=\pdiff{}{x}\big(x\big)
        +\pdiff{}{y}\big(y\big)
        +\pdiff{}{z}\big(z\big)
      =  3
      </mrow><mrow>
      \vnabla\times(x\,\vi+y\,\vj+z\,\vk)
      &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                        \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                        \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                        \pdiff{}{z} \\
                        x &amp; y &amp; z\end{matrix}\right]
      = \vZero
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(b)
      By definition
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla\cdot(xy^2\vi-yz^2\vj+zx^2\vk)
      &amp;=\pdiff{}{x}\big(xy^2\big)
        +\pdiff{}{y}\big(-yz^2\big)
        +\pdiff{}{z}\big(zx^2\big)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=y^2-z^2+x^2
      </mrow><mrow>
      \vnabla\times(xy^2\vi-yz^2\vj+zx^2\vk)
      &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                        \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                        \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                        \pdiff{}{z} \\
                        xy^2 &amp; -yz^2 &amp; zx^2\end{matrix}\right]
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;= 2yz\,\vi-2xz\,\vj-2xy\,\vk
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(c)
      By definition
      <md>
      <mrow>
      &amp;\vnabla\cdot\left(\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\vi+\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\vj\right)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.5in=\pdiff{}{x}\left(\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\right)
        +\pdiff{}{y}\left(\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\right)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.5in= \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}} - \frac{x^2}{{[x^2+y^2]}^{3/2}}
         +\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}} - \frac{y^2}{{[x^2+y^2]}^{3/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.5in=\frac{x^2+y^2\ -x^2\ +x^2+y^2\ -\ y^2}{{[x^2+y^2]}^{3/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.5in=\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\vnabla\times\left(\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\vi+\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\vj\right)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.5in=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                        \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                        \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                        \pdiff{}{z} \\
                        \frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}} &amp;
                        \frac{y}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}} &amp; 0\end{matrix}\right]
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.5in=\left(- \frac{xy}{{[x^2+y^2]}^{3/2}}+ \frac{xy}{{[x^2+y^2]}^{3/2}}\right)\vk
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.5in= \vZero
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(d)
      By definition
      <md>
        <mrow>
        &amp;\vnabla\cdot\left(-\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\vi+\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\vj\right)
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\hskip0.3in=\pdiff{}{x}\left(-\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\right)
          +\pdiff{}{y}\left(\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\right)
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\hskip0.3in=  \frac{xy}{{[x^2+y^2]}^{3/2}}
           - \frac{xy}{{[x^2+y^2]}^{3/2}}
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\hskip0.3in=0
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\vnabla\times\left(-\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\vi
                                 +\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\vj\right)
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\hskip0.3in=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                          \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                          \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                          \pdiff{}{z} \\
                          -\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}} &amp;
                          \frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}} &amp; 0\end{matrix}\right]
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\hskip0.3in=\!\left(\!\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}} - \frac{x^2}{{[x^2+y^2]}^{3/2}}
           +\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}} - \frac{y^2}{{[x^2+y^2]}^{3/2}}\!\right)\!\vk

        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\hskip0.3in= \frac{x^2+y^2\ -x^2\ +x^2+y^2\ -\ y^2}{{[x^2+y^2]}^{3/2}}\ \vk
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          &amp;\hskip0.3in= \frac{\vk}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}
        </mrow>
      </md>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2015A</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      Calculer et simplifier <m>\vnabla\cdot\big(\frac{\vr}{r}\big)</m>
      pour <m>\vr=(x,y,z)</m> et <m>r=|(x,y,z)|</m>. Exprimer la réponse en termes de <m>r</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
      Calculer <m>\vnabla\times\big(yz\,\vi + 2xz\,\vj + e^{xy}\,\vk\big)</m>.
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p>

      </statement>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>\frac{2}{r}</m></p><p>
      (b) <m>\big(xe^{xy}-2x\big)\,\vi+y\big(1-e^{xy}\big)\,\vj+z\,\vk</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p> (a)
       We are to compute the divergence of <m>\frac{\vr}{r}
      =\frac{x\,\vi+y\,\vj+z\,\vk}{[x^2+y^2+z^2]^{1/2}}</m>. Since
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \pdiff{}{x}\frac{x}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{1/2}}
      &amp;=\frac{1}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{1/2}}
                  -\frac{1}{2}\frac{x(2x)}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\frac{y^2+z^2}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      \pdiff{}{y}\frac{y}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{1/2}}
      &amp;=\frac{1}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{1/2}}
                  -\frac{1}{2}\frac{y(2y)}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\frac{x^2+z^2}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      \pdiff{}{z}\frac{z}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{1/2}}
      &amp;=\frac{1}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{1/2}}
                  -\frac{1}{2}\frac{z(2z)}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\frac{x^2+y^2}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      the specified divergence is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla\left(\frac{\vr}{r}\right) &amp;= \frac{2x^2+2y^2+2z^2}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
                                     =\frac{2r^2}{r^3}
                                     =\frac{2}{r}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(b)
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla\times\big(yz\,\vi + 2xz\,\vj + e^{xy}\,\vk\big)
      &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi&amp;\vj&amp;\vk\\
           \pdiff{}{x}&amp;
              \pdiff{}{y}&amp;
              \pdiff{}{z}\\
      yz&amp;2xz&amp;e^{xy}\end{matrix}\right]
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\big(xe^{xy}-2x\big)\,\vi-\big(ye^{xy}-y\big)\,\vj+z\,\vk
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      </solution>
    </exercise>


