    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Vérifier les identités vectorielles suivantes.
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      <m>\vnabla\cdot(f\vF)=f\vnabla\cdot\vF+\vF\cdot\vnabla f</m>
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>\vnabla\cdot(\vF\times\vG)
                            =\vG\cdot(\vnabla\times\vF)-
                             \vF\cdot(\vnabla\times\vG)</m>
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>\vnabla^2(fg)=f\,\vnabla^2 g+2\vnabla f\cdot\vnabla g+g\,\vnabla^2 f</m>
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p>

      </statement>

      <hint><p>
      Pour les parties (a) et (b), écrire les définitions des côtés gauche et droit et observer qu'ils sont égaux.
      La partie (c) peut être réalisée facilement en utilisant d'autres identités vectorielles plus simples.
      </p></hint>

      <answer>
        <p>
        (a) Par la règle du produit,
        <md>
        <mrow>
        \vnabla\cdot(f\vF)
        &amp;=\pdiff{}{x}(fF_1)
         +\pdiff{}{y}(fF_2)
         +\pdiff{}{z}(fF_3)
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;=\phantom{+}f\pdiff{F_1}{x}
         +f\pdiff{F_2}{y}
         +f\pdiff{F_3}{z}
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\phantom{=}+F_1\pdiff{f}{x}
         +F_2\pdiff{f}{y}
         +F_3\pdiff{f}{z}
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;=f\,\vnabla\cdot\vF+\vF\cdot\vnabla f
        </mrow>.
        </md>
        </p>

        <p>(b) Encore, par la règle du produit,
        <md>
        <mrow>
        &amp;\vnabla\cdot(\vF\times\vG)
        </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip0.25in=\pdiff{}{x}(F_2G_3-F_3G_2)
         +\pdiff{}{y}(F_3G_1-F_1G_3)
         +\pdiff{}{z}(F_1G_2-F_2G_1)
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\hskip0.25in=\phantom{+}\pdiff{F_2}{x}G_3
                -\pdiff{F_3}{x}G_2
         +\pdiff{F_3}{y}G_1
                - \pdiff{F_1}{y}G_3
         +\pdiff{F_1}{z}G_2
               - \pdiff{F_2}{z}G_1
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\hskip0.25in\phantom{=}+F_2\pdiff{G_3}{x}
               -F_3\pdiff{G_2}{x}
         +F_3\pdiff{G_1}{y}
               -F_1\pdiff{G_3}{y}
         +F_1\pdiff{G_2}{z}
              - F_2\pdiff{G_1}{z}
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\hskip0.25in=\phantom{+}
          \left(\pdiff{F_3}{y}-\pdiff{F_2}{z}\right)G_1
          +\left(\pdiff{F_1}{z}-\pdiff{F_3}{x}\right)G_2
          +\left(\pdiff{F_2}{x}-\pdiff{F_1}{y}\right)G_3
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\hskip0.25in\phantom{=}
          -F_1\left(\pdiff{G_3}{y}-\pdiff{G_2}{z}\right)
          -F_2\left(\pdiff{G_1}{z}-\pdiff{G_3}{x}\right)
          -F_3\left(\pdiff{G_2}{x}-\pdiff{G_1}{y}\right)
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;=\vG\cdot(\vnabla\times\vF)-
                               \vF\cdot(\vnabla\times\vG)
        </mrow>.
        </md>
        </p>

        <p>(c) Se rappeler que <m>\vnabla^2(fg) = \vnabla\cdot\big[\vnabla(fg)\big]</m>.
        Premièrement,
        <md>
        <mrow>
        \vnabla(fg)
        &amp;=\vi\pdiff{}{x}(fg)
         +\vj\pdiff{}{y}(fg)
         +\vk\pdiff{}{z}(fg)
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;=\phantom{+}\vi g\pdiff{f}{x}
         +\vj g\pdiff{f}{y}
         +\vk g\pdiff{f}{z}
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;\phantom{=}+\vi f\frac{\partial g}{\partial x}
         +\vj f\frac{\partial g}{\partial y}
         +\vk f\frac{\partial g}{\partial z}
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;=g\vnabla f+f\vnabla g
        </mrow>.
        </md>
        Donc, par la partie (a), deux fois,
        <md>
        <mrow>
        \vnabla^2(fg)
        &amp; = \vnabla\cdot\big(g\vnabla f\big)
           +\vnabla\cdot\big(f\vnabla g\big)
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;= g\big(\vnabla\cdot \vnabla f\big)
                  + \big(\vnabla g\big)\cdot\big(\vnabla f\big)
           +f\big(\vnabla\cdot\vnabla g\big)
               + \big(\vnabla f\big)\cdot\big(\vnabla g\big)
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;=f\,\vnabla^2 g+2\vnabla f\cdot\vnabla g+g\,\vnabla^2 f
        </mrow>.
        </md>
        </p>
      </answer>

      <solution><p>
      (a) Par la règle du produit,
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla\cdot(f\vF)
      &amp;=\pdiff{}{x}(fF_1)
       +\pdiff{}{y}(fF_2)
       +\pdiff{}{z}(fF_3)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\phantom{+}f\pdiff{F_1}{x}
       +f\pdiff{F_2}{y}
       +f\pdiff{F_3}{z}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\phantom{=}+F_1\pdiff{f}{x}
       +F_2\pdiff{f}{y}
       +F_3\pdiff{f}{z}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=f\,\vnabla\cdot\vF+\vF\cdot\vnabla f
      </mrow>.
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(b) Encore, par la règle du produit,
      <md>
      <mrow>
      &amp;\vnabla\cdot(\vF\times\vG)
      </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip0.25in=\pdiff{}{x}(F_2G_3-F_3G_2)
       +\pdiff{}{y}(F_3G_1-F_1G_3)
       +\pdiff{}{z}(F_1G_2-F_2G_1)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.25in=\phantom{+}\pdiff{F_2}{x}G_3
              -\pdiff{F_3}{x}G_2
       +\pdiff{F_3}{y}G_1
              - \pdiff{F_1}{y}G_3
       +\pdiff{F_1}{z}G_2
             - \pdiff{F_2}{z}G_1
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.25in\phantom{=}+F_2\pdiff{G_3}{x}
             -F_3\pdiff{G_2}{x}
       +F_3\pdiff{G_1}{y}
             -F_1\pdiff{G_3}{y}
       +F_1\pdiff{G_2}{z}
            - F_2\pdiff{G_1}{z}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.25in=\phantom{+}
        \left(\pdiff{F_3}{y}-\pdiff{F_2}{z}\right)G_1
        +\left(\pdiff{F_1}{z}-\pdiff{F_3}{x}\right)G_2
        +\left(\pdiff{F_2}{x}-\pdiff{F_1}{y}\right)G_3
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.25in\phantom{=}
        -F_1\left(\pdiff{G_3}{y}-\pdiff{G_2}{z}\right)
        -F_2\left(\pdiff{G_1}{z}-\pdiff{G_3}{x}\right)
        -F_3\left(\pdiff{G_2}{x}-\pdiff{G_1}{y}\right)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\vG\cdot(\vnabla\times\vF)-
                             \vF\cdot(\vnabla\times\vG)
      </mrow>.
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(c) Se rappeler que <m>\vnabla^2(fg) = \vnabla\cdot\big[\vnabla(fg)\big]</m>.
      Premièrement,
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla(fg)
      &amp;=\vi\pdiff{}{x}(fg)
       +\vj\pdiff{}{y}(fg)
       +\vk\pdiff{}{z}(fg)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\phantom{+}\vi g\pdiff{f}{x}
       +\vj g\pdiff{f}{y}
       +\vk g\pdiff{f}{z}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\phantom{=}+\vi f\frac{\partial g}{\partial x}
       +\vj f\frac{\partial g}{\partial y}
       +\vk f\frac{\partial g}{\partial z}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=g\vnabla f+f\vnabla g
      </mrow>.
      </md>
      Donc, par la partie (a), deux fois,
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla^2(fg)
      &amp; = \vnabla\cdot\big(g\vnabla f\big)
         +\vnabla\cdot\big(f\vnabla g\big)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;= g\big(\vnabla\cdot \vnabla f\big)
                + \big(\vnabla g\big)\cdot\big(\vnabla f\big)
         +f\big(\vnabla\cdot\vnabla g\big)
             + \big(\vnabla f\big)\cdot\big(\vnabla g\big)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=f\,\vnabla^2 g+2\vnabla f\cdot\vnabla g+g\,\vnabla^2 f
      </mrow>.
      </md>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="poisson"> <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2008A</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Dans ce qui suit, on utilise la notation
      <m>\vr = x\,\vi + y\,\vj + z\,\vk</m>, <m>r = |\vr|</m>, et <m>k</m> est un nombre
      <m>k = 0, 1, -1, 2, -2, \dots</m>
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      Trouver la valeur <m>k</m> pour laquelle <m>\vnabla (r^k) = -3\frac{\vr}{r^5}.      </m>
      </li>
      <li>
      Trouver la valeur <m>k</m> pour laquelle
      <m>
      \vnabla  \cdot (r^k\vr) = 5r^2.
      </m>
      </li>
      <li>
      Trouver la valeur <m>k</m> pour laquelle
      <m>
      \vnabla^2 (r^k) = \frac{2}{r^4}.
      </m>
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <hint><p>
      (c) peut être fait de façon efficace en utilisant (a) et (b).
      </p></hint>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>k=-3</m></p><p>
      (b) <m>k=2</m></p><p>
      (c) <m>k=-2</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p> (a)
      Since <m>r^k=\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{k/2}</m>,
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \pdiff{}{x} r^k
         &amp; = 2x\ \frac{k}{2}\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{\frac{k}{2}-1}
           = k\ (\vr\cdot\vi)\ r^{k-2}
      </mrow><mrow>
      \pdiff{}{y} r^k
         &amp; = 2y\ \frac{k}{2}\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{\frac{k}{2}-1}
           = k\ (\vr\cdot\vj)\ r^{k-2}
      </mrow><mrow>
      \pdiff{}{z} r^k
         &amp; = 2z\ \frac{k}{2}\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{\frac{k}{2}-1}
           = k\ (\vr\cdot\vk)\ r^{k-2}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      We want <m>k=-3</m>.
      </p>

      <p>(b) Using the computation in part (a)
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla  \cdot (r^k\vr)
      &amp;= \pdiff{}{x} (x r^k)
        + \pdiff{}{y} (y r^k)
        + \pdiff{}{z} (z r^k)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;= 3r^k + x \pdiff{}{x} r^k
        + y \pdiff{}{y} r^k
        + z \pdiff{}{z} r^k
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;= 3r^k + x \big(kx\ r^{k-2}\big)
        + y \big(ky\ r^{k-2}\big)
        + z \big(kz\ r^{k-2}\big)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;= \big(3+k\big)r^k
      </mrow>
      </md>
      We want <m>k=2</m>.
      </p>

      <p>(c) Recalling that
      <m>\vnabla^2 = \vnabla\cdot\vnabla</m>,
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla^2 (r^k )
      &amp;=\vnabla\cdot\big(\vnabla(r^k)\big)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\vnabla\cdot(k r^{k-2}\,\vr) &amp;\text{by part (a)}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=k(3+k-2)r^{k-2} &amp;\text{by part (b),  but with <m>k</m> replaced by <m>k-2</m>}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      We want <m>k=-2</m>.
      </p>

      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2017A</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Soit <m>\vr</m> le champ de vecteurs <m>\vr = x\,\vi + y\,\vj + z\,\vk</m> et soit
      <m>r</m> la fonction <m>r = |\vr|</m>. Soit <m>\va</m> le vecteur <em>constant</em>
      <m>\va = a_1\,\vi + a_2\,\vj + a_3\,\vk</m>. Calculer et simplifier
      les quantités suivantes.
      Les réponses doivent être exprimées en termes de <m>\va</m>, <m>\vr</m> et <m>r</m>. Il ne devrait pas y avoir de
      <m>x</m>, <m>y</m> ou <m>z</m> dans les réponses.
      <ol marker = "(a)" cols = "2">
      <li>
      <m>\vnabla\cdot\vr</m>
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>\vnabla(r^2)</m>
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>\vnabla\times(\vr\times\va)</m>
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>\vnabla\cdot\big(\vnabla(r)\big)</m>
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>3</m></p><p>
      (b) <m>2\vr</m></p><p>
      (c) <m>-2\va</m></p><p>
      (d) <m>\frac{2}{r}</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p> (a)
      <me>
      \vnabla\cdot\vr
      =\pdiff{x}{x}
        +\pdiff{y}{y}
        +\pdiff{z}{z}
      =3
      </me>
      </p>

      <p>(b)
      <me>
        \vnabla(r^2)
        =\left(\vi\pdiff{}{x}
          +\vj\pdiff{}{y}
          +\vk\pdiff{}{z} \right)
        \big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)
        =2x\,\vi +2y\,\vj +2\,\vk
        =2\vr
      </me>
      </p>

      <p>(c) Since
      <me>
      \vr\times\va = \det\left[\begin{matrix}
                               \vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                                x  &amp;  y  &amp; z   \\
                               a_1 &amp; a_2 &amp; a_3
                               \end{matrix}\right]
                    =\vi\big(a_3y\!-\!a_2z\big)
                    +\vj\big(a_1z\!-\!a_3x\big)
                    +\vk\big(a_2x\!-\!a_1y\big)
      </me>
      we have
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla\times(\vr\times\va)
      &amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi&amp;\vj&amp;\vk \\
           \pdiff{}{x}&amp;
              \pdiff{}{y}&amp;
              \pdiff{}{z} \\
          a_3y-a_2z&amp; a_1z-a_3x &amp; a_2x-a_1y\end{matrix}\right]
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=-2a_1\,\vi -2a_2\,\vj -2a_3\,\vk
      </mrow><mrow>
       &amp;=-2\va
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(d) Since
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla(r) &amp;= \left(\vi\pdiff{}{x}
        +\vj\pdiff{}{y}
        +\vk\pdiff{}{z} \right) \big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\vi\frac{x}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}}
        +\vj\frac{y}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}}
        +\vk\frac{x}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      we have
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla\cdot\big(\vnabla(r)\big)
      &amp;= \pdiff{}{x} \frac{x}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}}
         +\pdiff{}{y} \frac{y}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip1in +\pdiff{}{z} \frac{z}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=  \frac{3}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}}
         -\frac{1}{2}\frac{2x^2+2y^2+2z^2}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{3/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp; =\frac{2}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp; =\frac{2}{r}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2017D</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Soit <m> \vr = x\,\vi + y\,\vj + z\,\vk </m> et <m> r = |\vr|</m>.
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      Calculer <m>a</m>, où <m>\vnabla\big(\frac{1}{r}\big) =- r^a\,\vr</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
      Calculer <m>a</m>, où <m>\vnabla\cdot\big(r\,\vr\big) = ar</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
      Calculer <m>a</m>, où <m>\vnabla\cdot\big(\vnabla(r^3)\big) = ar</m>.
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>a=-3</m></p><p>
      (b) <m>a=4</m></p><p>
      (c) <m>a=12</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p> (a)
      Since
      <md>
      <mrow>
      &amp;\vnabla\left(\frac{1}{r}\right)
      = \left(\vi\pdiff{}{x}
        +\vj\pdiff{}{y}
        +\vk\pdiff{}{z} \right) \big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{-1/2}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.25in=-\vi\frac{x}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{3/2}}
        -\vj\frac{y}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{3/2}}
        -\vk\frac{z}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{3/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.25in=-\vi\frac{x}{r^3}
        -\vj\frac{y}{r^3}
        -\vk\frac{x}{r^3}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      we have <m>a=-3</m>.
      </p>

      <p>(b) Since
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla\cdot\big(r\,\vr\big)
      &amp;= \pdiff{}{x} \Big[\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}x\Big]
         +\pdiff{}{y}\Big[\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}y\Big]
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip1in +\pdiff{}{z} \Big[\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}z\Big]
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=  3\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}
         +\frac{1}{2}\frac{2x^2+2y^2+2z^2}{\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp; =4\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp; =4r
      </mrow>
      </md>
      we have <m>a=4</m>.
      </p>

      <p>(c) Since
      <md>
      <mrow>
      &amp;\vnabla(r^3) = \left(\vi\pdiff{}{x}
        +\vj\pdiff{}{y}
        +\vk\pdiff{}{z} \right) \big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{3/2}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.1in=\vi\,3x\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}
        +\vj\,3y\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}
        +\vk\,3z\big(x^2+y^2+z^2\big)^{1/2}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip0.1in=3r\vr
      </mrow>
      </md>
      we have
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla\cdot\big(\vnabla(r^3)\big)
      &amp;= \vnabla\cdot\big(3r\vr\big)
      = 3\,\vnabla\cdot\big(r\vr\big)
      = 3\,\big(4r\big) \qquad\text{by part (b)}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=  12 r
      </mrow>
      </md>
      so that <m>a=12</m>.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Trouver, si possible, un champ de vecteurs <m>\vA</m> qui a pour composante <m>\vk</m>
      <m>A_3=0</m> et qui est un potentiel vectoriel pour
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li> <m>\vF=(1+yz)\vi+(2y+zx)\vj+(3z^2+xy)\vk</m>.
      </li>
      <li> <m>\vG= yz\vi+zx\vj+xy\vk</m>.
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>\vF</m> ne peut avoir un potentiel vectoriel.
      </p>

      <p>(b) Deux solutions possibles sont
      <m>\vA=\frac{1}{2}(z^2-y^2)x\vi-\frac{1}{2} yz^2\vj</m> et
      <m>\vA=\frac{1}{2} xz^2\vi+\frac{1}{2}(x^2-z^2)y\vj</m>.
      </p>

      </answer>

      <solution><p>
      (a) Since
      <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF
      =\pdiff{}{x}(1+yz)+\pdiff{}{y}(2y+zx)+\pdiff{}{z}(3z^2+xy)=2+6z\ne 0</m>,
      <m>\vF</m> fails the screening test and cannot have a vector potential.
      </p>

      <p>(b) The vector field <m>\vA=A_1\vi+A_2\vj</m> is a vector
      potential for <m>\vG</m> if and only if <m>\vG=\vnabla\times\vA</m>,
      which is the case if and only if
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      -\pdiff{A_2}{z}&amp;= yz\quad &amp;
            \iff&amp;\quad&amp;
            &amp;A_2=-\frac{1}{2} yz^2+B_2(x,y)
      </mrow><mrow>
      \pdiff{A_1}{z}&amp;=zx &amp;
             \iff&amp;\quad &amp;
            &amp;A_1=\phantom{-}\frac{1}{2} xz^2+B_1(x,y)
      </mrow><mrow>
      \pdiff{A_2}{x}-\pdiff{A_1}{y} &amp;=xy &amp;
           \iff&amp; &amp;  &amp;
         \pdiff{B_2}{x} -\pdiff{B_1}{y}=xy
      </mrow>
      </md>
      There are infinitely many solutions to <m>\pdiff{B_2}{x}
      -\pdiff{B_1}{y}=xy</m>. In fact <m>B_2</m> is completely arbitrary.
      If one chooses <m>B_2=0</m>, then <m>B_1=-\frac{1}{2} xy^2</m> does the job. If one chooses
      <m>B_1=0</m>, then <m>B_2=\frac{1}{2} x^2y</m> does the job. Thus two solutions are
      <m>\vA=\frac{1}{2}(z^2-y^2)x\vi-\frac{1}{2} yz^2\vj</m> and
      <m>\vA=\frac{1}{2} xz^2\vi+\frac{1}{2}(x^2-z^2)y\vj</m>.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2006D</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Soit
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vF = \frac{-z}{x^2+z^2}\,\vi +y\,\vj +\frac{x}{x^2+z^2}\,\vk
      </mrow>.
      </md>
      </p>

      <p><ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      Déterminer le domaine de <m>\vF</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
      Déterminer le rotationnel de <m>\vF</m>. Simplifier si possible.
      </li>
      <li>
      Déterminer la divergence de <m>\vF</m>. Simplifier si possible.
      </li>
      <li>
      Est-ce que <m>\vF</m> est conservatif? Donner une raison pour la réponse.
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>D=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+z^2\ne 0}</m></p><p>
      (b) <m>\vnabla\times\vF=\vZero</m> sur <m>D</m></p><p>
      (c) <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF=1</m> sur <m>D</m>
      </p>

      <p>(d) <m>\vF</m> n'est pas conservatif sur le domaine <m>D</m> de la partie (a).
      </p>

      </answer>

      <solution><p>(a) <m>\vF</m> is well-defined wherever the denominator
      <m>x^2+z^2</m> is nonzero. So the (largest possible) domain is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      D=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+z^2\ne 0}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p> (b)
      As preliminary computations, let's find
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \pdiff{}{z}\left(\frac{-z}{x^2+z^2}\right)
      &amp;=\frac{-1}{x^2+z^2}-\frac{2z(-z)}{{(x^2+z^2)}^2}
      =\frac{-x^2+z^2}{{(x^2+z^2)}^2}

      </mrow><mrow>
      \pdiff{}{x}\left(\frac{x}{x^2+z^2}\right)
      &amp;=\frac{1}{x^2+z^2}-\frac{2x(x)}{{(x^2+z^2)}^2}
      =\frac{-x^2+z^2}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      So the curl of <m>\vF</m> is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla\times\vF
      &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
      \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk \\
      \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                      \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z} \\
      \frac{-z}{x^2+z^2} &amp; y &amp; \frac{x}{x^2+z^2}
      \end{matrix}
      \right]
      =-\left(\frac{-x^2+z^2}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}
        -\frac{-x^2+z^2}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}\right)\vj
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\vZero
      </mrow>
      </md>
      <em>on the domain of <m>\vF</m></em>.
      </p>

      <p> (c)
      As preliminary computations, let's find
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \pdiff{}{x}\left(\frac{-z}{x^2+z^2}\right)
      &amp;=-\frac{2x(-z)}{{(x^2+z^2)}^2}
      =\frac{2xz}{{(x^2+z^2)}^2}
       </mrow><mrow>
      \pdiff{}{z}\left(\frac{x}{x^2+z^2}\right)
      &amp;=-\frac{2z(x)}{{(x^2+z^2)}^2}
      =\frac{-2xz}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      So the divergence of <m>\vF</m> is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla\cdot\vF
      &amp;=\pdiff{}{x}\left(\frac{-z}{x^2+z^2}\right)
        +\pdiff{}{y}\left(y\right)
        + \pdiff{}{z}\left(\frac{x}{x^2+z^2}\right)
      =1
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p> (d)
      By part (b), the vector field passes the conservative field screening test
      <m>\vnabla\times\vF=\vZero</m>. But we should still be suspicious because
      of the similarity of <m>\vF</m> to the vector field of
      Examples <xref ref="eg_screeningCounterexample"/> and <xref ref="ex-green-bord-x2"/>.
      </p>

      <p>So let's compute the line integral of <m>\vF</m> around the (closed) circle
      <m>y=0</m>, <m>x^2+z^2=1</m>, parametrized by
      <me>
      \vr(t) = \cos t\,\vi +\sin t\,\vk\qquad
      \vr'(t) = -\sin t\,\vi +\cos t\,\vk
      </me>
      The line integral is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \int_C \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}
      &amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}\!\!\big\{
             \overbrace{-\sin t}^{\frac{-z}{x^2+z^2}}\,\vi
            +\overbrace{\cos t}^{\frac{x}{x^2+y^2}}\,\vk\big\}
                 \cdot
        \big\{\overbrace{-\sin t\,\vi +\cos t\,\vk}^{\vr'(t)}\big\}\dee{t}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;= \int_0^{2\pi}\dee{t}
      =2\pi
      </mrow>
      </md>
      As the integral of <m>\vF</m> around the simple closed curve <m>\cC</m>
      is not zero, <m>\vF</m> cannot be conservative on <m>D</m>.
      See Theorem <xref ref="thm_pathIndepConserv"/> and
      Examples <xref ref="eg_screeningCounterexample"/> and <xref ref="ex-green-bord-x2"/>.
      </p>

      </solution>
    </exercise>

    
    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2004A</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Un physicien étudie un champ de vecteurs <m>\vF</m> dans son laboratoire. Il sait, d'après des considérations théoriques, que <m>\vF</m> doit être de la forme
      <m>\vF=\nabla\times\vG</m>, pour un certain champ de vecteurs lisse <m>\vG</m>. Des expériences
      montrent également que <m>\vF</m> doit être de la forme
      <me>
      \vF(x,y,z)=(xz+xy)\vi+\alpha(yz-xy)\vj+\beta(yz+xz)\vk
      </me>,
      où <m>\alpha</m> et <m>\beta</m> sont des constantes.
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      Déterminer <m>\alpha</m> et <m>\beta</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
      Des expériences supplémentaires montrent que <m>\vG=xyz\vi-xyz\vj+g(x,y,z)\vk</m>.
      Trouver la fonction inconnue <m>g(x,y,z)</m>.
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p>

      </statement>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>\alpha=\beta=-1</m>
      </p>

      <p>(b)  N'importe quelle fonction de la forme <m>g(x,y,z)=xyz+w(z)</m> fonctionne.
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      (a)
      By the vector identity of Theorem <xref ref="thm_degTwoIdentities"/>.a,
      <me>
      \nabla\cdot \vF=\nabla\cdot \nabla\times\vG=0
      </me>
      So we must have
      <md>
      <mrow>
      0&amp;=\nabla\cdot\vF=\nabla\cdot \big((xz+xy)\vi+\alpha(yz-xy)\vj+\beta(yz+xz)\vk\big)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=(z+y)+\alpha(z-x)+\beta(y+x)
      </mrow>
      </md>
      This is true for all <m>(x,y,z)</m> if and only if <m>\alpha=\beta=-1</m>.
      </p>

      <p>(b) Since
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \nabla\times\vG&amp;=\nabla\times\big(xyz\vi-xyz\vj+g(x,y,z)\vk\big)
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=(g_y+xy)\,\vi-(g_x-xy)\,hj+(-yz-xz)\,\vk
      </mrow>
      </md>
      we will have that <m>\nabla\times\vG=\vF</m> if and only if
      <md>
      <mrow>
      &amp;(g_y+xy)\,\vi-(g_x-xy)\,\vj+(-yz-xz)\,\vk
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\hskip1in=(xz+xy)\,\vi-(yz-xy)\,\vj-(yz+xz)\,\vk
      </mrow>
      </md>
      which is the case if and only if
      <me>
      g_y=xz,\quad g_x=yz
      </me>
      The first equation, <m>g_y=xz</m>, is satisfied if and only if <m>g=xyz+h(x,z)</m>.
      The second equation is also satisfied if and only if
      <m>g_x=yz+h_x(x,z)=yz</m>. This is the case if and only if <m>h_x(x,z)=0</m>. That
      is, if and only if <m>h</m> is independent of <m>x</m>. Equivalently, if and only
      if <m>h(x,z)=w(z)</m> for some function <m>w(z)</m>. So, in fact, any function of
      the form <m>g(x,y,z)=xyz+w(z)</m> will work.
      </p>

      </solution>
    </exercise>

